Use ASP.NET Core's **`WebApplicationFactory<T>`** — it hosts your app in-memory and gives you an `HttpClient` that talks to it without opening a real port.

**1. Add the test project dependencies:**

```xml
<PackageReference Include="Microsoft.AspNetCore.Mvc.Testing" Version="9.0.*" />
<PackageReference Include="xunit" Version="2.*" />
```

**2. Write a test class:**

```csharp
public class McpIntegrationTests : IClassFixture<WebApplicationFactory<Program>>
{
    private readonly HttpClient _client;

    public McpIntegrationTests(WebApplicationFactory<Program> factory)
    {
        _client = factory.CreateClient();
    }

    [Fact]
    public async Task Initialize_ReturnsCapabilities()
    {
        var request = new
        {
            jsonrpc = "2.0",
            id = 1,
            method = "initialize",
            @params = new
            {
                protocolVersion = "2025-03-26",
                capabilities = new { },
                clientInfo = new { name = "test-client", version = "1.0" }
            }
        };

        var response = await _client.PostAsJsonAsync("/mcp", request);

        response.EnsureSuccessStatusCode();
        var body = await response.Content.ReadFromJsonAsync<JsonElement>();
        Assert.Equal("2.0", body.GetProperty("jsonrpc").GetString());
        Assert.Equal(1, body.GetProperty("id").GetInt32());
        Assert.True(body.GetProperty("result").TryGetProperty("capabilities", out _));
    }

    [Fact]
    public async Task ToolsCall_ExecutesTool()
    {
        // Initialize first (stateful servers need this)
        await InitializeSession();

        var request = new
        {
            jsonrpc = "2.0",
            id = 2,
            method = "tools/call",
            @params = new
            {
                name = "my-tool",
                arguments = new { input = "hello" }
            }
        };

        var response = await _client.PostAsJsonAsync("/mcp", request);

        response.EnsureSuccessStatusCode();
        var body = await response.Content.ReadFromJsonAsync<JsonElement>();
        var content = body.GetProperty("result").GetProperty("content");
        Assert.False(content.EnumerateArray().First()
            .TryGetProperty("isError", out _));
    }
}
```

**Key points:**

- **No real port** — `WebApplicationFactory` uses an in-memory test server via `TestServer`.
- **Swap dependencies** — override `ConfigureWebHost` to replace real services (DBs, APIs) with fakes.
- **SSE endpoints** — for Streamable HTTP (`Accept: text/event-stream`), read the response stream line-by-line and parse `data:` lines as JSON-RPC messages.
- **Session state** — if your server uses `Mcp-Session-Id`, capture it from the `initialize` response and send it as a header on subsequent requests.
- Make sure your `Program` class is accessible (add `public partial class Program { }` at the bottom of `Program.cs` if needed).
